{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868880/1930061901/0128.xml":{"full_text":"TTie Milwaukee Leader\nPrivate Power Makes\nAnother Demand\nApparently the power people overstepped themselves in asking\nFrederic M. Sackett, United States ambassador to Germany, to alter\nhis speech before the world power conference.\nFrom their point of view it would have been all right if it had\nworked, but it became public, and we are much mistaken if there\nwill not be numerous repercussions. The people of this country\nhave not yet forgotten the revelations concerning private power\nactivities which came out of the Federal Trade Commission\u2019s in\nvestigation.\nAmbassador Sackett is a former power man himself, and he is\nalso a conservative, hence his statements derogatory to the way the\npower industry is being operated cannot be discounted as the rav\nings of a radical.\nListen to this from his speech, you payers of electric bills: \u201cI\nknow of no other manufacturing industry where the sale price of\nthe product to the great mass of consumers is fifteen times the\nactual cost of production of the article sold.\u201d\nHe warned the private power magnates that \u201cyou who are in\nthis business should remember that among the users of your product\nthe class which is the greatest in number and constitutes the basis\nof that public opinion which in the end judges and controls public\nutilities is that vast body of men who every month pay a 6-cent\ncharge in their households for an article which we are constantly\ntold is being produced by efficient electric stations for from three\ntenths to four-tenths of a cent.\u201d\nHe was speaking accurately when he said that this vast body\nof consumers \u201cin the,end\u201d controls public utilities. In the mean\ntime they pay the exorbitant rates and let the private power folks\nget away with it. But \u201cin the end\u201d let us hope they will wake up\nand take control.\nThe high rates are due to private ownership and nothing else.\nUnder private ownership there are high dividends to pay to\nstockholders and high interest to pay to bondholders. The courts\npermit outrageously high valuations upon which to base high rates.\nThe stocks and bonds do not decrease\u2014they constantly increase\u2014\nand the consumers have to put up, in the form of rates, the money\nto pay the increased dividends and interest.\nAll this could be eliminated by public ownership.\nYou would get your electric juice at cost, as you do postage\nstamps. If the postal service were owned by a private corporation,\nwith the usual flood of stocks and bonds, yoft would in all prob\nability pay somewhere from a dime to a quarter for the delivery of\na letter.\nALOOF FROM THE LOVE\nFEAST\nThe Chicago Tribune says that Wiscon\nsin is in a dilemma because the standpat\nRepublicans and the progressive Repub\nlicans agree on the issues, hence there is\nnothing for them to fight about.\nThey are both against chain banks and\nchain stores, it says, and neither of them\npropose any remedy. They are both willing\nto have lower utility rates. And the Demo\ncrats chime in with the Republicans.\nThere needn\u2019t be v a lack of political and\neconomic discussion on this account. The\nSocialists have definite ideas on these issues\n\u2014and the Socialist candidate for governor,\nFrank B. Metcalfe, will tell \u2019em about it.\nThe Socialists are in favor of having\nchain banks and chain stores owned by the\npublic so that they can be operated for the\nbenefit of the public. They do not merely\nmake pious wishes for lower utility rates,\nbut they stand for public ownership of\npublic utilities so that lower rates can\nactually be realized.\nThese are excellent samples of the good\nthings in the Socialist state platform.\nCopies of that document can be had from\nthe state office in Brisbane Hall. It ought\nto be placed in the hands of every voter in\nthe state.\nANOTHER IF\nThe maximum income tax rate in this\ncountry is 20 per cent, while in England it\nis about 47 per cent\u2014over twice as high,\nbut not high enough.\nSince England was much harder* hit by\nthe war than our country, this higher rate\nonly brings in enough for ordinary pur\nposes, and it is hard to squeeze out any\nthing for public works to furnish employ\nment; but it helps to pay unemployment\ninsurance.\nThere never was any good excuse for\nlowering the income taxes of the rich in this\ncountry, as has been done several times\nsince the close of the war. If we even had\nas high a rate as England, there would be\nfunds with which to start public works and\ngive employment to large numbers of un\nemployed. To begin paying them wages\nwould help to boost industry all along the\nline. They do not even get unemployment\ninsurance here.\nThe great working class, which does\nmost of the suffering from poverty and un\nemployment, has neglected to use its power.\nVast numbers of workers have neglected to\njoin the unions, and still larger numbers\nhave neglected to make proper use of their\nballots. It is natural that they should be\ntreated to a robber tariff to piuck money\nfrom their pockets for the benefit of\nwealthy industrial overlords, instead of\ngetting relief from unemployment and\npoverty..\nEDITORS\u2019\nWhat Do You\nThink About It?\nQUOTATIONS.\nTo the Editor:\nThe following may be of inter\nest to Dan Rossoll: \u201cGo to,\nnow, ye rich men, weep and howl\nfor your miseries that shall come\nupon you.\n\u201cYour riches are corrupted, and\nyour garments are moth eaten.\n\u201cYour gold and silver are can\nkered and the rust of them shall\nbe a witness against you, and\nshall eat your flesh as it w r ere\nfire. Ye have heaped treasure to\ngether for the last days.\n\u201cBehold, the hire of the labor\ners who have reaped down your\nfields, which is of you kept back\nby fraud, crieth; and the cries of\nthem which have reaped are en\ntered into the ears of the Lord of\nSabaoth.\n\u201cYe have lived in pleasure on\nthe earth, and been wanton; ye\nhave nourished your hearts, as in\nthe day of slaughter. .Ye have\ncondemned and killed the just;\nand he doth not resist you.\u201d\nThe passage you quote, Rossoll,\nmay not be in the Bible, but the\nforegoing is. It is easy to find in\nthe fifth chapter of James. James\ncould not better describe present\nday conditions were he living\namong us today.\nIn my boyhood days in lowa\nland and homes could be had here\nfor little more than the asking\nand making, but today, in one of\nthe best agricultural states of the\nunion, conditions are as James\ndescribed them in verse four.\nSacco and Vanzetti are dead.\nDebs and Rutherford were im\nprisoned and their lives short\nened: By whom? by the rich ex\nploiters of this nation.\nSocialists, pacifists and Chris\ntians were persecuted and killed\nduring the war, and the end is not\nyet. Read once more verse six,\nthen the following:\n\u2018\u2018But in the last days\u201d (of the\npresent unjust order), \u201cit shall\ncome to pass that the mountain\nof the house of Lord\u201d (the\nkingdom of God), \u201cshall be estab\nlished in the top of the moun\ntains,\u201d (over all nations and\nkingdoms) \u201cand it shall be exalt\ned above the hills; and people\nshall flow into it.\u201d\nRead on through the second\nand third verses and then the\nfourth: \u201cBut they shall sit every\nman under his vine and under\nhis fig tree; and none shall make\nthem afraid; for the mouth of the\nLord hath spoken it.\u201d\nThe second Bible quotation is\nin the fourth chapter of Mieah,\nfirst four verses. The bracketed\nportions are the best explanations\nthat I know of. based on the prin\nciple of comparing scripture with\nscripture to learn its meaning.\nWhat do you think of it? I\nwould like to comment but have\nexceeded my limit. N. B, S.\nlowa.\nWANT OSCAR.\nTo the Editor:\nWelcome back dear old Oscar\nAmeringer, alias \u201cAdam Coaldig\nger!\u201d We have missed you long!\nReading your contribution in the\nissue of June 14 was like shak\ning hands with a dear old friend.\nWe admire Heywood Broun,\nand enjoy the write-ups by E. L.\nMeyer, but there is only one Os\ncar Ameringer. We want you\nback on The Leader.\nAUGUSTA and ALFRED E.\nCORTEZ.\nRoute No. 1. Box 104 A, South\n___ Milwaukee. JVis,\nTHE NAVAL TREATY\nBY NORMAN THOMAS.\nIf there is any one lesson that history teaches\nfrom the time of the Pharaohs down to Mussolini,\nit is that no one nation can ever be strong enough\nto keep peace by its. own force. Whatever else it\nis, peace is a matter of international agreement.\nCompetitive nationalist armaments necessarily cre\nate fear and suspicion and make war more not less\nlikely. Disarmament or limitation of armaments\nalone is not a patent medicine for the evil of war\nbut it is good for much in the struggle for peace.\nHow are those who believe in these general\nprinciples going to apply them to the London naval\ntreaty\nI think we must say that although the London\nnaval treaty is decidedly unsatisfactory the failure\nof the United States senate to ratify it would be\na hard blow to our hope of peace. The reason that\nit is important to ratify an unsatisfactory treaty is\nthat defeat of the treaty would be a victory for the\nroaring rear admirals, the Tories, and the milita\nrists in every country, and not for those of us who\nare dissatisfied because the treaty did so little.\nMoreover, the critics of the treaty have brought it\nto pass that in Japan, and possibly in England,\ndefeat of the treaty would be taken as a direct\nblow to limitation of armaments by agreement, a\nslur on their sincerity and a direct challenge to a\nnaval race.\nThe treaty does not actually reduce fleets in\nbeing. It does not even save us much on the build\ning program to which congress has been committed.\nIt does, however, save us a good deal on such a\nprogram as the British advocated at Geneva and\nthe American admirals advocated after Geneva.\nOf course, it saves us an enormous amount on the\ncost of an unlimited naval race, both in money and\nin good will. Moreover we do not have to build up\nto the maximum figures permitted by the treaty.\nNeither does England nor Japan.\nA second objection to the treaty is that in its\nmost important points it is a three and not a five\npower treaty. France and Italy are out and they\nmay upset the apple cart. The so-called \u201cescape\nclause\u201d which is article 21 of the treaty, inserted\nat the request of Great Britain, gives any one of\nthe three signers a right, upon notification to the\nother signers, to exceed the limitations in a given\nclass of ships imposed by the treaty if it thinks\nthis necessary because of the naval program of any\npower which did not sign the treaty. In plain\nEnglish this means that a naval race between\nFrance and Italy, which did not sign the treaty,\nmay make Gi\u2019eat Britain feel that she must increase\nher building in order to live up to the unwritten\nlaw that her navy must be as strong as any two\nEuropean powers. Such building would pretty well\nknock the treaty into a cocked hat. It is, however,\nby no means certain that France and Italy will\nforce their building to such an extent during the\nlife of the treaty. And it is exceedingly unlikely\nthat a Labor or Liberal government in Great Brit\nain would find it politically wise to provoke the\nUnited States to fresh building by taking advan\ntage of article 21. Moreover article 21, itself, sug\ngests the possibility of diplomatic consultation be\nfore actual new building is begun.\nWhat worries our admirals and our jingoistic\neditors and senators is not so much these things,\nhowever, as the question whether or not the treaty\ngives us parity with Great Britain.\nNow', this parity business is an impossible and\ndangerous fetish. If mean the Kellogg treaty\nseriously and are not going to fight, parity doesn\u2019t\nmatter much, or rather the logical parity would be\nzero, that is naval disarmament. If there is danger\nw'e are going to fight we want not parity but su\nperiority, at least for aggressive v r ars. For a de\nfensive war, as the last war proved, a smaller navy\nin home waters can more than hold its own.\nFinally, there are so many elements that go into\nparity, including not only the size of the navy but\nthe number of merchant ships, the economic re\nsources of thp country, etc., that no absolute for\nmula for parity can ever be devised.\nThe best argument that the treaty gives some\nthing like a fair compromise is the fact that the\nTories and admirals in England and Japan oppose\nit on exactly the same grounds as their colleagues\nin America.\nSome enterprising lecture bureau ought to ex\nchange admirals, the Americans to tell the British\nhow we got gypped by the treaty, and the British\nto tell us how they were robbed. f\nIt never will be possible to get limitation by\nagreement if the naval general staff of each coun\ntry is going to insist on its own program at all\ncosts. For us to have argued for twenty-one 8-inch\ncruisers or nothing would have meant no treaty or,\nat best, a treaty to inci-ease navies. Perhaps the\nadvocates of the treaty in America, including the\nminority of admirals, are wrong in arguing, as they\ndid, that for certain purposes. at least, the 6-inch\ngun cruisers are as good. The majority of our\nnaval board may be right on that technical matter;\nwe can afford to admit that. The agreement on\ncruisers was a compromise in order to get any\ntreaty. The British gave up their demand for limit\ning the size of 6-inch gun cruisers to less than\n10,000 tons and they came way down froip their\nGeneva figures. The Japanese also made conces\nsions. That was the price of the treaty. If we\nbad been willing to make more concessions to meet\nthe hints or open suggestions of the English there\nwould have been further reduction of battleships or\naircraft carriers Our admirals blocked that, which\nis one more victory than they ought to have won.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nPublished in Milwaukee. Wis.. every afternoon ex\ncept Sunday EDITORIAL AND PUBLICATION\nOFFICES: 528-32 Juneau Avenue at Sixth Street.\nTelephones Marquette 7500.\nE. J. COSTELLO. Editor.\nAssociate Editor. John M. Work: Managing Editor,\nLeo Wolfsohn: City Editor. Frank Haggerty: Sports\nEditor. Ben Smith: Advertising Manager Elmer A.\nKrahn.\nEntered as second class matter Augaist 25, 1920, at the\npostoffiec at Milwaukee. Wis.. under the act of March 3. 1879\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\u2014MaiI editions in United\nStates: Three months. $1.50: six months. $3: one\nyear. $6. To foreign countries: Three months $3:\nsix months. S 6: one vear Sl2.\nThe home edition is delivered by carriers in Mil\nwaukee and county for 15 cents a week or 65 cents a\nmonth: elsewhere by carrier. 18 cents a week or 80\ncents a month.\nADVERTISING subiect to publisher\u2019s acceptance.\nRates on application. FOREIGN ADVERTISING\nREPRESENTATIVES: Fralick. Bates Alward. Inc.\nNew York: 270 Madison Avenue. Room 1301. Chicago:\n605 North Michigan Avenue. San Francisco and Loa\nAngeles.\nAPfsffiffi] COUNCIL\nDifficult Decisions\no\nKNOTTY PROBLEM OF PROCEDURE\nARISING WHEN A STRANGE DOG. OF\nUNCERTAIN LOOKING DISPOSITION, AP\nPROPRIATED THE TEAM'S ONE AND ONLY BALL.\nOiOVAS\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Bell Syndicate, Inc>\n[CHICAGO \u2014The population of\nChicago was announced as 3,373,-\n753, an inciease of 672,048 since\nthe 1920 census. Chicago thus en\ntered the third million, ranking\nas second city in the nation and\nfourth in the world. Announce\nment of the census figures was\nhailed by a city-wide celebration\nin the schools and business\nhouses, and downtown Chicago\npoured showers of ticker tape and\nconfetti from its windows.\u2014News\nItem.]\nThere is beauty in bigness;\nthere is virtue in size. Bigness\nlends distinction, power, grandeur\nWisconsin Views\nBased upon the uniformity of\nthe suicide rate in Wisconsin dur\ning the past 22 years, we can pre\ndict with a great deal of accuracy\nthe actual number of persons who\nwill commit suicide in Wisconsin\nduring the present year or even\nnext year. For the calendar year\nof 1929 the state has recorded 451\ndeaths from suicides. This is a\nlarger number than has ever been\nrecorded in Wisconsin during any\none year. The death rate from\nsuicides per 100.000 population\nwas also higher in 1929 than for\nany other year. The lowest su\nicide rate was for 1920 when the\nrate was 10.1 per 100,000 popula\ntion. The rate in 1929 was 15.5.\nThere has been a slight increase\nin the death rate from suicides in\nWisconsin each year since 1923.\nThe following is a tabulation\nshowing the various types of su\nicides based on the means em\nployed in destroying life for 1929:\nSuicide by poison 50\nSuicide by poison gas 29\nSuicide by hanging ISS\nSuicide by drowning 30\nSuicide by firearms 124\nSuicide by cutting or piercing\ninstruments 18\nSuicide by jumping from high\nplaces 7\nSuicide by crushing 4\nOther suicides 4\nA study has been made showing\ndeaths from suicides by months\nfor the period from 1908 to 1929.\nThis tabulation shows there is a\nvery decided seasonal variation in\nthe number of deaths from su\nicides. The maximum number of\ndeaths per month is reached each\nyear during the early summer,\nusually in May or June. In Wis\nconsin, many people, in fact we\nbelieve the vast majority of peo\nple. consider May and June the\nmost attractive months in the\nyear and it is difficult to under\nstand why suicides should be so\nnumerous during these months.\nWe naturally would expect com\nparatively few deaths from\ndrowning during the winter\nmonths when practically all our\nlakes and streams are covered\nwith ice, but drowning is not one\nof the favorite methods employed\nin self-destruction. For January,\n1929. there were no suicides from\ndrowning; there was only one for\nthe month of February and six\nfor the month of March. One su\nicide from drowning was reported\nfor the month of September, one\nfor October and one for November\nand none for December.\nThe real causes for suicide are\ndifficult to understand and it is\nespecially puzzling to account for\nthe large number of suicides dur\nmg the spring months. Consider\ning the problem on a purely\nphysiological basis, we perhaps\nare warranted in assuming that\npeople are more apt to have at\ntacks of melancholia in a climate\nsuch as we have in Wisconsin\nduring the springtime than at\nother seasons. This, we believe,\nis especially true of people who\nlive sedentary lives, who consume\nlarge Quantities of heatproducing\nfoods during the wintertime with\nfaulty elimination. The spring\ntonic which people used to think\nSECTION\nMAKING UGHT OF THE TIMES\nand renown. Bigness is the god\nwe worship the ideal we sweat\nfor, the truth we lie about. Aye,\nbigness is big.\nSo sings Chicago. Chicago with\nthree millions.\nThe city sings its triumph of\nthree million. Child voices sound\nin the schools, chanting the litany\nof bigness. Whistles blow and\nbells toll, proclaiming the magic\nof three millions; business men\nspeak solemnly and with awe to\naudiences listening with awe, and\nfrom, the windowed turrets of the\nboulevard float clouds of confetti\nas bigness is crowned king.\nChicago has three millions. Chi\ncago has three millions. Men go\nhoarse shouting the tidings, and\nmen are shaken with hysterical\nzeal as they yield themselves to\nthe religion of numbers. Bigness\nis god. Hallelujah!\nChicago has three millions.\nWhom shall we count in the three\nmillions?\nwas very necessary is perhaps a\nfeeble attempt to meet a condition\nof bodily discomfort and a gener\nal feeling of ill-health which peo\nple so often experience in the\nearly spring. Better than sulphur\nand molasses, swamp root or\nether so-called blood purifiers\nwould be a visit to your family\nphysician in the early spring. If\nyou have no physician and that\n\u2018\u2022gone feeling\u201d comes over you, the\nbest advice we can give anyone is\nto consult some sympathetic doc\ntor, lay your case before him and\nfollow his advice as to what you\nshould do.\nThe physiological changes which\ntake place in our systems during\nthe change from winter to sum\nmer living are, of course, only one\nof the causes of suicides. The keen\ncompetition in every line of hu\nman endeavor and the inability on\nthe part of many unfortunate\npersons to successfully compete\nwith their fellows are unquestion\nably among the chief causes of\ndespondency and suieide. Ill\nhealth is another important fac\ntor. In many cases this is real\nand in other cases only imaginary.\nA physician can be of great serv\nice in these cases. Some member\nof the family should make it his\nbusiness to see to it that the suf\nferer is given proper medical ad\nvice. Unquestionably the high su\nicide rate in 1929 and some of the\nsuicides reported thus far in 1930\nare a direct result of the financial\ndepression and the stock market\ncrash last fall. Suicides always\nincrease during such periods,\n\u2014L. W. H., in State Board of\nHealth Bulletin.\nWhat was the population of\nthis country before the white men\ncame? How many men, women\nand children then lived in what\nis now the United States?\nThis is a hard question to an\nswer since then there were no\ncensus-takers or census reports.\nWe can only estimate the popu-\nlation from the number of In\ndian arrowheads, hammerstones\nend other tools we find and from\nthe graves, village sites and\nmounds which the Indians left\nbehind them.\nFrom this, we find that no part\nof the present United States was\nuninhabited, ''\u2019he Indian popula\ntion was loosely, spread over the\nBY E. L. KEYER\nShall we count the man with\nWONDERS of the WORLD com. a win... ph.o\nBEFORE COLUMBUS.\nBY GLUYAS WILLIAMS\nfurtive eyes who lives in the\nshadow of the loop and creeps,\nwith night, through the street,\nwaylays his victim, and vanishes\ncat-like before dawn slides into\nthe alleys? Shall we count him?\nAye, we shall count him, for\nwithout him there can be no big\nness, and without bigness we\nwould be lost. So we shall count\nhim, while he is washing the\nblood from his hands. He shall\ndo his bit tor bigness, and shall\nbe forgiven. Hallelujah!\nShall we count the beer-run\nners, the ward-heelers, the\napaches, ike blackmailers, the\nkidnapers, the 10,000 racketeers,\nthe crooktd politicians, the cor\nrupt policemen, the gamblers, the\ntipsters, the black-handers, the\nextortionists, the gansters and\nthe makers and throwers of\nbombs? Shall w T e count them?\nAye, they shall go in. They\nshall beccne a part of the big\nness we c ould not do without\nthem. And the convicts in Bride\nwell shall go in, too, and swell\nthe total to three millions, and\nbells shall ling out as a tribute\nto their virtue in letting them\nselves be counted. Praise God,\nthey shall go in.\nShall we count the dweller in\nthe mansions who have made\ntheir fortunes on stolen fran\nchises, bribes, war profits, blood\nprofits and looting of the public\ntreasury? Shall we count them?\nAye, we shall count them. We\nshall count them twice if we can,\nfor they merit the honor. They\nare the boosters of bigness, the\nchampions of bigness and without\nthem the temple of highness\nwould lack prophets with big\nvoices and we would be lambs\nwithout leaders. They shall go\nin. Hallelujah Hallelujah\nm\nChicago with three millions.\nWhom shall we count in the three\nmillions? Shall we count the\nshop-girls crowding the L\u2019s, the\nsmudgy dinner-pail brigades\nclumping through the factory\ngates at vvl;istle-blow, the street\nsweeper, the palid women cough\ning in the fumes of a chemical\nplant, the army toiling in the\nsmells of packing-town, the pick\nand-shovel-D-,en, the Negroes at\nthe river wharf, the soap-makers\nat the lye vats, the machine ten\nders and the dish washers? Shall\nwe count them?\nAye, we shall count them. They\nshall become a part of the big\nness and rejoice.\nWe shall count, too, the old, the\ndiscarded, the maimed and the\nsick. We shall count, the old\nwoman in the bread line who\nentire country. It followed espe\ncially the streams and the shores\nof lakes. The Indians seem to\nhave reached the heads of all the\nstreams great and small, which\nfinally flow into the Mississippi.\nThe Cumberland and Tennessee\nvalleys have been carefully\nsearched to find out how many\nIndians lived there. After 40\nBfPoHe wrtire hts\nCArir ra AKeHitA\nVRohABUV UveT> I*\ntWe va uceys thc\nte k ivr** Ax\nCIIMB EXuArWD \"fclvnW\n1 AIS\nears of study, it is said that at\n(ne time there were probably\n100,000 Indians in these two val\nleys alone.\nWhen we remember all the vast\nriver systems in the United\nStates, we can see from this that\nthe Indian population must have\nbeen much larger before the com\ning o\u00a3 toe vvlute man, than it i$\n1 Thursday, June 19, 1930\nSplinters\nAnd another thing the country\nneeds is a good 5-eeut shine.\nWeeds, according to the farm\nboard, cost the country three bil\nlion a year\u2014not counting the\nwidows\u2019.\nPublishers who think there is\nno profit in fiction that paints\nthe brighter side haven\u2019t seen the\nnew resort literature.\nThese private polls may be use\nful. but they don\u2019t seem to af\nfect the constitution or the price\nof liquor.\nTalkies didn\u2019t originate the\nidea. The war gave us that great\ntheme song Mademoiselle from\nArmentieres.\n\u201cThe American woman looks\ndissatisfied.\u201d thinking\nwhat she could do with the ali\nmony the first wife is getting.\nThe rich have fewer children.\nOr perhaps, lacking children,\nthey just have to get rich enough\nto hire servants instead.\nAmericanism: Cheering be\ncause the town has gained a few\nthousand unimportant inhabi\ntants growling because you\ncan\u2019t find a decent parking place.\nWhen you don\u2019t know whether\nto say \u201cI should\u201d or \u201cI would,\u201d\nthe correct form is \u201cI\u2019d.\u201d\nOne cause of crime usually\noverlooked by great minds is the\nfact that a great many people\nare ornery.\nAmong the enterprises that put\nmoney in circulation to hasten\nthe return of prosperity are\nprimaries.\nLaundries found a cleaning\nagent that would remove dirt\nwithout destroying the fabric,\nPerhaps in time they will find\none that won\u2019t eat off the but\ntons.\nOver here it is merely a co-ed's\ndream, but, Oxford actually al\nlows one girl student to each four\nmen.\nStill, the cost of entering the\nsenate doesn't seem so great when\nyou reflect on the sum four aces\ncan collect in that society.\nBut think how often the sti*-\npid Indifference of the people has\nkept us from following brilliant\nleaders In the wrong direction.\nCorrect this sentence. \u201cI\nwouldn\u2019t care for bridge,\u201d said\nthe husband, \u201ceven if I could\nbeat all the women In our set.\u201d\nstirs her thin soup and mumbles\nher bread and stares with rheu\nmy eyes into her bowl. Aye, even\nshe shall share In the beauty of\nbigness. Cup your hand to your\near old woman, and hear the bells\ntoll, the children sing and the\nprophets with big voices boom\ning the triumph of the three mil\nlion. This is your triumph and\nyour day, too, old woman. Toil\nhave done your bit for bigness,\nyou have been counted, and your\nspirit should be big with ectasy\nas you contemplate what you\nhave done lor bigness and what\nbigness has done for you. Halle\nlujah\n\nListen while Chicago sings its\ntriumph of three millions. Child\nvoices sound in the schools, chant\ning the litany of bigness. Whistles\nblow and bells toll, proclaiming\nthe magic of three millions, and\nfrom windowed turrets on the\nsunlit-boulevard float clouds of\nconfetti as bigness is crowned\nking.\nListen.\nIn the shadows behind the\nyards, in the shadows that lie\neternally under the smoke-pall\nwhere faciory chimneys spew, in\nthe shadows everywhere are\nshadows of men, listening. Listen\ning to the far, faint hallelujahs\nfrom the sun-lit boulevard. Halle\nlujah hallelujah.\ntoday. Tuberculosis, smallpox\nand other diseases which the\nwhite men brought, wii>ed out\nwhole tribes. The theft of the\nIndians\u2019 lands and the wars\nfought against them make one of\nthe bad chapters in our history.\nWe should now pursue a better\npolicy if we want to save the\nremnants of this once great peo\nple.\nHow long bad the Indians lived\nhere before Columbus came? This\nis another puzzling question.\nThere are many reasons for think\ning that they were not newcom\ners.\nIn the Florida shell mounds,\nskeletons have been found at a\ngreat depth. These mounds are\nvery old. One skull was crusted\nover with shells cemented to it.\nJn the Ozark caves, stalagmites\nhave formed over human remains.\nForm many parts of the country\nstone weapons and tools have\nbeen found which are weather\nbeaten by the ages. Some have\neven begun to disintegrate.\nThese are some of the reasons\nwhy learned men say the Indians\nhave been here at least three or\nfour thousand years\u2014very likely,\nmuch longer.\nNext\u2014An Ogre With a Pious\nPose.\n(Copyright, IHSO. by Republic Syn,di-<\ncate, Inc.),","height":"28587","width":"21150"}}
